# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: base-on-balls
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:base-on-balls/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:base-on-balls/1887-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1887 throughout the world.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The **1889 major league baseball season** began on April 17, 1889.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 15, with the New York Giants and the Brooklyn Bridegrooms as regular season champions of the National League and American Association, respectively.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the sixth World's Championship Series on October 18 and ended with Game 9 on October 29, in what was a best-of-eleven-playoff.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The Giants defeated the Dodgers, six games to three, capturing their second consecutive World's Championship Series.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] Over the offseason, the National League's Detroit Wolverines folded, and saw them replaced by the American Association's Cleveland Blues, renamed to the Cleveland Spiders.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] In Cleveland's AA place, the Columbus Solons were enfranchised.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] This was the final season of the NL's Indianapolis Hoosiers & Washington Nationals, and the AA's Kansas City Cowboys.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The 1889 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place by the American Association since the 1886 season and by the National League since the previous season.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] American Association Opening Day took place on April 17 featuring four teams, while National League Opening Day took place on April 24, featuring all eight teams.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 15 with four teams playing, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 5, featuring all eight teams.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The 1889 World's Championship Series took place between October 18 and October 29.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams of the American Association (which was informally referred to as the "Beer & Whiskey League" due to its openness on alcohol, compared to the National League) to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] Initial version of stadium burned in a fire in mid-May and was rebuilt in time before the need for a neutral site.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] 26 tie games (13 in AA, 13 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The Columbus Solons join the American Association and play at Recreation Park in Columbus, Ohio.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] Following their eviction from the original Polo Grounds in New York, New York over the offseason, the New York Giants would play at several ballparks while waiting for their next home further uptown, also called the Polo Grounds, to finish construction.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The team would play at Oakland Park in Jersey City, New Jersey for two games on April 24 and 25, before beginning play at the St.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] George, New York, the former home of the New York Metropolitans, where they played from April 29 through June 14.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] Following a road trip, the team would begin play at the new Polo Grounds on July 8.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] A fire at Washington Park, home of the Brooklyn Bridegrooms occurred on May 17 while the team was on a road trip.
[src:base-on-balls/1889-major-league-baseball-season] The burnt down grandstand and fencing were rebuilt in time for the team to play their next scheduled home game, on May 30.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The **1890 major league baseball season** began on April 17, 1890.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The National League and newly founded Players' League regular seasons ended on October 4, with the Boston Beaneaters and Boston Reds as the NL and PL pennant winners, respectively.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association regular season ended on October 15 and saw the Louisville Colonels the winners of the AA pennant.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason between the AA and NL began with Game 1 of the seventh World's Championship Series on October 17 and ended with Game 7 on October 28.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The series ended in a tie, with the Bridegrooms and Colonels each with three wins, and a tie game.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The series was unique in that the Bridegrooms reached the series back-to-back, but with each season in a different league, a feat that has not been matched since.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The Reds had floated a three-way Championship series with them and the AA & NL pennant winners, though the idea fell on deaf ears.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] This was the final season of a dual-league championship until the founding of the modern World Series in 1903 between the National League and American League.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The major league world was in turmoil in 1890, as many of the best players had jumped to the "outlaw" Players' League.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] Although the Brotherhood only lasted the one season, it had a detrimental financial effect on the other two leagues, especially the Association, who would not survive the following season, merging into the National League in December 1891.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] Over the prior offseason, the Indianapolis Hoosiers and Washington Nationals of the National League, and Kansas City Cowboys of the American Association folded.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The major-league status of the Federal League was confirmed by the Special Baseball Records Committee (as convened by then-Commissioner of Baseball William Eckert) in 1969.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The 1890 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American Association, National League, and Players' League, each of which had eight active teams (the Baltimore Orioles would finish the Brooklyn Gladiators' schedule once they folded following their last game on August 25).
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place by the American Association since the 1886 season and by the National League since the 1888 season.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] American Association Opening Day took place on April 17 featuring six teams, while National League and Players' League Opening Days took place on April 19, each featuring their eight teams.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 15 with a doubleheader between the Baltimore Orioles and Rochester Broncos.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the season on October 4, with a doubleheader between the Philadelphia Phillies and Cleveland Spiders.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The Players' League would see its season end on the same day, with all eight teams playing.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The 1890 World's Championship Series took place between October 17 and October 28.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The 1890 season featured an extremely rare tripleheader—the first of three in National League and major-league history, when the Brooklyn Bridegrooms hosted the Pittsburgh Alleghenys on September 1 for three games.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Gladiators, Cleveland Spiders, and Pittsburgh Alleghenys played in 17 neutral site games in which they were treated as the home team.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] 31 tie games (15 in AA, 9 in NL, 7 in PL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] Only records for National League teams are available.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] With the Brooklyn Bridegrooms transferring to the National League, which bans Sunday games, their three-season tenure playing Sunday games at Ridgewood Park in Ridgewood, New York ends.
[src:base-on-balls/1890-major-league-baseball-season] The 1890 season saw six teams playing at their respective ballparks for the last time, five of which moved into new ballparks for the start of the 1891 season while one team, the Brooklyn Gladiators, folded mid-season.
[src:base-on-balls/1891-major-league-baseball-season] The **1891 major league baseball season** was contested from April 8 through October 6, 1891.
[src:base-on-balls/1891-major-league-baseball-season] It was the final season for the American Association (AA), with the Boston Reds winning the AA pennant.
[src:base-on-balls/1891-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Boston Beaneaters won the NL pennant.
[src:base-on-balls/1891-major-league-baseball-season] The Reds, following the 1890 Brooklyn Bridegrooms consecutive pennant wins 1889–1890 in different leagues, also followed such a feat, winning the since folded Players' League's 1890 pennant and becoming the second and last team to win consecutive pennants in different leagues.
[src:base-on-balls/1891-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season since 1883 which saw no postseason, due to a breakdown in relations between the American Association and National League prior to the start of the season.
[src:base-on-balls/1891-major-league-baseball-season] The next championship series would take place the following season in a unique split season format, due to negotiations during the merger of the AA into the NL.
[src:base-on-balls/1891-major-league-baseball-season] The unstable American Association would see that 1891 would be its final season, before merging into the National League the following season; the four clubs that would continue on were the Baltimore Orioles, Louisville Colonels, St.
[src:base-on-balls/1891-major-league-baseball-season] The other four AA clubs, the Boston Reds, Columbus Solons, Milwaukee Brewers, and Philadelphia Athletics), saw their owners paid $135,000 (equivalent to $4,837,500 in 2025) and their players dispersed to the surviving twelve clubs.
[src:base-on-balls/1891-major-league-baseball-season] The 1891 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight active teams (the Milwaukee Brewers would finish the Cincinnati Kelly's Killers' schedule once they folded following their last game on August 16).
[src:base-on-balls/1891-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place by the American Association since the 1886 season and by the National League since the 1888 season, and was the last season this format would be used until the National League contracted from twelve to eight teams in 1900.
[src:base-on-balls/1891-major-league-baseball-season] American Association Opening Day took place on April 8 featuring all eight teams, while National League Opening Day would not take place for another two weeks on April 22, also featuring all eight teams.
[src:base-on-balls/1891-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 6, while the National would see its final day of the season on October 3.
[src:base-on-balls/1891-major-league-baseball-season] The Milwaukee Brewers hosted a neutral site game in Minneapolis, Minnesota against the Columbus Solons.
[src:base-on-balls/1891-major-league-baseball-season] 19 tie games (12 in AA, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:base-on-balls/1891-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in *italics* indicates a team a player was on from a different league.
[src:base-on-balls/1891-major-league-baseball-season] Any stat from said different league is not calculated to determine the league leader.
[src:base-on-balls/1891-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Colts begin playing at South Side Park, splitting their season from West Side Park.
[src:base-on-balls/1891-major-league-baseball-season] They would play their final game at West Side Park on October 2 against the Cincinnati Reds, permanently moving into South Side Park for the start of the 1892 season.
[src:base-on-balls/1891-major-league-baseball-season] American Park, the home of the Cincinnati Reds, is renamed to League Park.
[src:base-on-balls/1891-major-league-baseball-season] After the Cincinnati Outlaw Reds folded mid-season, the Milwaukee Brewers withdrew from the Western League as a replacement team, playing at Brewer Field.
[src:base-on-balls/1891-major-league-baseball-season] The team plays one of their 21 home games at a neutral site in Athletic Park in Minneapolis, Minnesota.
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] The **1892 major league baseball season** began on April 12, 1892.
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] Unique to National League history, the season was organized into a split season format, with July 14 being the split date between the two half seasons.
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 15, with the Boston Beaneaters as the pennant winner of the National League overall, as well as the first-half champions, with the Cleveland Spiders as second-half champions.
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the eighth and final World's Championship Series on October 17 and ended with Game 6 on October 24.
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] Aside from a tie game, the Beaneaters swept the Spiders with five wins in the best-of-nine playoff, and therefore winner of the final Dauvray Cup.
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] This was Boston's only pre-modern championship.
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] The 1892 season saw the return of a postseason championship series (albeit a one-off of this format), following the demise of the American Association.
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] The one-off was the first since the 1890 World's Championship Series.
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] The next championship series would take place in 1894 via the Temple Cup.
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] The demise of the American Association saw four of its teams merged into the National League, including the Baltimore Orioles, Louisville Colonels, St.
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns, and Washington Statesmen (renamed as the Washington Senators).
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] The four other American Association clubs active at the end of the previous season, the Boston Reds, Columbus Solons, Milwaukee Brewers, and Philadelphia Athletics), saw their owners paid $135,000 (equivalent to $4,837,500 in 2025) and their players dispersed to the surviving clubs.
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] The 1892 schedule consisted of 154 games for the twelve teams of the National League.
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other eleven teams in the league.
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] This replaced the 140-game, 20-games-each against seven-teams format previously used by the National League since 1888 and defunct-American Association since 1886.
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] The 140-game format would return in 1900.
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 12 featuring all twelve teams.
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] Each half of the season was split by an off day on July 14.
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 15 and also featured all twelve teams.
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] The 1892 World's Championship Series took place between October 17 and October 24.
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] 18 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] Values in parentheses show first-half and second-half ties.
[src:base-on-balls/1892-major-league-baseball-season] Having previously split their time in two ballparks for the 1891 season, the Chicago Colts permanently leave the site of West Side Park after playing there for seven seasons since 1885 in favor of South Side Park.
[src:base-on-balls/1893-major-league-baseball-season] The **1893 major league baseball season** began on April 27, 1893.
[src:base-on-balls/1893-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 30, with the Boston Beaneaters as the pennant winner of the National League and therefore winner of the final Dauvray Cup.
[src:base-on-balls/1893-major-league-baseball-season] The 1893 season saw no postseason championship series, unlike the split-season 1892 World's Championship Series.
[src:base-on-balls/1893-major-league-baseball-season] This would not last, as the following season would see the Temple Cup, which would be a championship series between the NL pennant winner and the runner-up.
[src:base-on-balls/1893-major-league-baseball-season] The 1893 schedule consisted of 132 games for the twelve teams of the National League.
[src:base-on-balls/1893-major-league-baseball-season] This replaced the 154-game, 14-games-each format put in place in the previous season and would be used until 1898.
[src:base-on-balls/1893-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 27 featuring eight teams.
[src:base-on-balls/1893-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, featuring six teams.
[src:base-on-balls/1893-major-league-baseball-season] 12 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:base-on-balls/1893-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns leave Sportsman's Park (where they played for 11 seasons) and move to New Sportman's Park, where they would go on to play for 28 seasons through part of 1920.
[src:base-on-balls/1893-major-league-baseball-season] The ballpark for the Louisville Colonels, Eclipse Park was largely destroyed in a fire towards the end of the previous season, though the team continued to play in its remains.
[src:base-on-balls/1893-major-league-baseball-season] In the 1893 season, the Colonels played only one home game on May 4 at the still destroyed ballpark.
[src:base-on-balls/1893-major-league-baseball-season] They would move one block south at a new ballpark, also named Eclipse Park, when they returned home for their next home game on May 22.
[src:base-on-balls/1893-major-league-baseball-season] When the World's Columbian Exposition in Chicago opened in May, the Chicago Colts wanted to break with their no-Sundays tradition and start playing Sunday games to attract Fair visitors, but their South Side Park lease forbade Sunday ball.
[src:base-on-balls/1893-major-league-baseball-season] They sought a new location, which turned out to be West Side Park.
[src:base-on-balls/1893-major-league-baseball-season] After drawing well on their two May Sunday games, the club abandoned their three-season tenure at South Side Park after only eight games (their last being on May 24) and moved to the West Side on a full-time basis from their next home game on Sunday, June 18.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] A **base on balls** (**BB**), better known as a **walk**, occurs in baseball when a batter receives four pitches during a plate appearance that the umpire calls *balls*, and is in turn awarded first base without the possibility of being called out.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] The base on balls is defined in Section 2.00 of baseball's Official Rules, and further detail is given in 6.08(a).
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] Despite being known as a "walk", it is considered a faux pas for a professional player to actually walk to first base; the batter-runner and any advancing runners normally jog on such a play.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] The term "base on balls" distinguishes a walk from the other manners in which a batter can be awarded first base without liability to be put out (e.g., hit by pitch (HBP), catcher's interference).
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] Though a base on balls, catcher's interference, or a batter hit by a pitched ball all result in the batter (and possibly runners on base) being awarded a base, the term "walk" usually refers only to a base on balls, and not the other methods of reaching base without the bat touching the ball.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] An important difference is that for a hit batter or catcher's interference, the ball is dead and no one may advance unless forced; the ball is live after a walk (see below for details).
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] A batter who draws a base on balls is commonly said to have been "walked" by the pitcher.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] When the batter is walked, runners advance one base without liability to be put out only if forced to vacate their base to allow the batter to take first base.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] If a batter draws a walk with the bases loaded, all preceding runners are forced to advance, including the runner on third base who is forced to home plate to score a run; when a run is forced on a walk, the batter is credited with a run batted in per rule 9.04.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] Receiving a base on balls does not count as a hit or an at bat for a batter but does count as a time on base and a plate appearance.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] Therefore, a base on balls does not affect a player's batting average, but it can increase his on-base percentage.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] A hit by pitch is not counted statistically as a walk, though the effect is mostly the same, with the batter receiving a free pass to first base.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] One exception is that on hit-by-pitch, the ball is dead, and any runners attempting to steal on the play must return to their original base unless forced to the next base anyway.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] When a walk occurs, the ball is still live: any runner not forced to advance may nevertheless attempt to advance at his own risk, which might occur on a steal play, passed ball, or wild pitch.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] Also, because a ball is live when a base on balls occurs, runners on base forced to advance one base may attempt to advance beyond one base, at their own risk.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] The batter-runner himself may attempt to advance beyond first base, at his own risk.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] Rule 6.08 addresses this matter as well.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] An attempt to advance an additional base beyond the base awarded might occur when ball four is a passed ball or a wild pitch.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] In early baseball, there was no concept of a "ball".
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] In 1869 the rule was modified so that only those baserunners forced to advance could advance.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] From 1871 through 1886, the batter was entitled to call "high" or "low", i.e. above or below the waist; a pitch which failed to conform was "unfair".
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] Certain pitches were defined as automatic balls in 1872: any ball delivered over the batter's head, that hit the ground in front of home plate, was delivered to the opposite side from the batter, or came within one foot of him.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] In 1880, the National League changed the rules so that eight "unfair balls" instead of nine were required for a walk.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] In 1884, the National League changed the rules so that six balls were required for a walk.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] In 1886, the American Association changed the rules so that six balls instead of seven were required for a walk; however, the National League changed the rules so that seven balls were required for a walk instead of six.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] In 1887, the National League and American Association agreed to abide by some uniform rule changes, including, for the first time, a strike zone which defined balls and strikes by rule rather than the umpire's discretion, and decreased the number of balls required for a walk to five.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] In 1889, the National League and the American Association decreased the number of balls required for a walk to four.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] In 2017, Major League Baseball approved a rule change allowing for a batter to be walked intentionally by having the defending bench signal to the umpire.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] A subset of the base on balls, an intentional base on balls (IBB), or intentional walk, is when the defensive team intentionally issues a walk to the batter.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] In Major League Baseball and many amateur leagues, an intentional base on balls is signaled to the home plate umpire by the defensive team's manager holding up four fingers, at which point the batter is awarded first base without any further pitches being thrown.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] As with any other walk, an intentional walk entitles the batter to first base without liability to be put out, and entitles any runners to advance if forced.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] Intentional walks are a strategic defensive maneuver, commonly done to bypass one hitter for one the defensive team believes is less likely to initiate a run-scoring play (e.g., a home run, sacrifice fly, or RBI base hit).
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] Teams also commonly use intentional walks to set up a double play or force out situation for the next batter.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] Jimmie Foxx, Andre Thornton, Jeff Bagwell and Bryce Harper have each been walked six times during a major league regular season game.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] Among pitchers, Tommy Byrne and Bruno Haas both gave up 16 bases on balls in a game.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] On September 17, 1920, the Boston Red Sox drew 20 walks in a 12-inning game against the Detroit Tigers.
[src:base-on-balls/base-on-balls] As of September 2024, this is the most walks drawn or allowed by a team in a single game in Major League history according to available data.
